and health institutions, called bureaux de la santé, were developed. Contributions to this book primarily focus on health vigilance from the standpoint of how to prevent an epidemic and how to respond to a declared epidemic. Among the salient themes addressed are: communications between health and different state actors, prevailing religious and political norms, and the popular participation in the fight against the plague. The use of the concept of vigilance enables the mobilisation of often rather distant branches of history, namely institutional. social, religious history, the history of communication and the history of public health.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 7aHISTORY / Modern / 17th Century.2bisacsh  aAttentiveness, Pestilence, Marseille, coast.1 aBeauvieux, Fleur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBertrand, Régis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBusch, Thorsten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButi, Gilbert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemichel, Sébastien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemichel, Sébastien, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHengerer, Mark Sven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHengerer, Mark Sven, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVidoni, Nicolas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb0 cEPUBz97831110262440 cprintz978311102612140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783111026169zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783111026169zOpen Access7